  "prompt": "Why does ISKCON deny Lord Shiva's Supremacy?",
  "response": "ISKCON (International Society for Krishna Consciousness) adheres to the theological principles rooted in Gaudiya Vaishnavism, which is a tradition within Hinduism focusing on the worship of Lord Krishna as the Supreme Personality of Godhead. Followers of ISKCON believe that Krishna is the ultimate, supreme deity and all other gods are subordinate to Him. \n\nIn this tradition, Lord Shiva is highly respected and venerated, but he is viewed as one of the demigods who serve a specific role within the cosmic order. Gaudiya Vaishnavism teaches that while Lord Shiva holds a crucial role as the destroyer and transformer within the universe, he is ultimately not the Supreme Being. \n\nThe theological foundation for this belief comes from texts such as the Bhagavad Gita and various Vaishnava scriptures, which emphasize Krishna's supreme position. However, it is important to note that \"denying Lord Shiva's supremacy\" doesn't equate to disrespecting him; ISKCON devotees respect and honor Shiva's significant role but maintain the belief that Krishna is the Supreme Lord.\n\nDifferent Hindu traditions may have varying interpretations of the hierarchy and relationships among deities, which is why the perception of supremacy might differ. It's essential to understand these differences in the context of their specific theological frameworks.",
